column2: i have never felt less alone. in the wake of #metoo and dr. ford’s testimony
column3: i think many of us have finally understood how the world can shift from telling the truth. how a belief in my voice can help another woman believe in hers. how we are all connected. how what has kept us silent is not realizing that we have the force of love in our favor. how we are actually the majority. and that we matter. we just need to keep getting louder and louder so we can find each other

column1: 314045;instagram;2018-10-05 16:02:40;FALSE;"self care for survivors of sexual assault & harassment #metoo | self care friday with synolve
for those of us who have been publicly humiliated
column9: the past couple of weeks with the kavanaugh hearings and his nomination for supreme court justice and even this past year has been painful and disturbing. i stand with dr. christine blasey ford and every woman who has been victimized and traumatized. it is important that despite what has happened that we as survivors take a moment to take care of ourselves and love ourselves. if you need to seek a counselor or therapist
column10: then do so. post traumatic stress disorder can plague survivors long after the trauma has occurred. the hearings and negative things that are being said by high ranking officials and how victims have been treated during the kavanaugh hearings has been difficult to understand and process. often this brings up difficult emotions and many survivors relive their own personal stories during times like these.

column1: i just want to encourage you.
nurture your voice and inner spirit.
know when you need a break.

column3: and radio when you need to do so.

column1: be around people who love and care about you and your story...people you trust to be loving
we have the power of our voice.
no one can take that away.
we won’t stop telling our stories and our truth.

column1: 314065;instagram;2018-10-05 16:05:31;FALSE;"u.s. president donald trump said tuesday that it's a ""very scary time for young men......”.
the president has come to the defence of young (presumably white
column4: who suddenly find their reputations and livelihood threatened a year after the #metoo whirlwind first swept on to the scene.

column1: as a husband and a father to three incredible daughters i do not see this as a scary time for young men. i see this an important period in time where we men
column2: young and old have to step up and start being men
column4: not pubescent boys in adult skin and cloth. we need to start looking at this time differently

column1: consciousness is clearly showing us something here and we need to take a good hard look in the mirror and start questioning whether we are being the best example of man for the next generations of men
ask the question; am i showing the world all of my amazing positive masculine attributes?

column1: 314085;instagram;2018-10-05 15:52:19;FALSE;"full video on igtv **trigger warning** self care during black fridays & kavaughn vote

veronica shares how she is taking care of herself this week and some practices she uses. she stresses it is ok to not engage in this moment in anyway because your mental health and healing is more important. the greatest change we can make in the world is to heal ourselves which sends our ripples of positive change in every aspect of our lives.

she also gives her thoughts on what this moment means for our county and the important choice we have to make whether to continue to fuel hate/rage/divisiveness or to create spaces for everyone to come together from a place of love and healing. we hope you all choose to join us in making this a healing moment.
for those with children here is a great article from @greenchildmag  on natural treatments for childhood anxiety:
as always she loves your messages

column1: 314092;instagram;2018-10-05 15:54:04;FALSE;"today we wear black in solidarity with women across our nation to say enough is enough. today i wear black to show my daughters that we do have a voice.  today i will not shop
column2: i will make phone calls to senators
column3: and i will write ford to thank her for putting her life on the line for all us and our daughters of future generations.  i believe ford.  i question whether or not i shield my daughters from the ugliness that happens around them.  but instead i share the reality
column6: and empower them with tools along the way.  i do this for them. i do this because i believe when more women stand up
column9: the world will be a better place.  i will continue to find ways to channel my rage to be a fiercely compassionate activists in the world.

column1: 314125;instagram;2018-10-05 15:40:41;FALSE;"“we have nothing to lose but our chains.” — .

column2: protesters gathered all over the country to unite against president donald trump’s supreme court nominee
column3: brett kavanaugh. put another way: protesters gathered to show their support for professor christine blasey ford
column4: who came forward with accusations against kavanaugh
column6: and the #metoo movement. the us senate is closing in on holding a procedural vote for kavanaugh’s nomination into the supreme court later today
column7: most likely sealing a conservative majority and ending just a week’s long investigation into **potential** sexual misconduct.

column2: put on by harvard’s international socialist group
column3: was held at the steps of john harvard in harvard yard while (during the opening remarks) a choir sang “america the beautiful” in perfect harmony in the background. (the irony was haunting.)

column1: i ask you to question how elite institutions like kavanaugh’s yale and harvard
column2: contribute to sexual assault and gender based inequality at large? and more importantly
column3: what are you doing to combat these same injustices? .

column1: this is my small thing. (and it is only a small thing.) but i am choosing to purposely interrupt the usual type of photos i post on this page to say something that i hope you have already heard
column2: and that i can only hope to amplify
column4: no mater the outcome. these women
column5: and every other person who has been the victim of sexual assault and misconduct deserve to have their stories validated. this is my small effort to say that “you are not alone. that i believe you. that even if your government does not
column6: i will still believe you. and your brave act of coming forward despite the consequences is not in vain.”

column2: i have my first official spread to share with you all! but before i dive into that
column3: there is some necessary background information that informs the spread…

column1: i recently became aware that mars
column3: is leaving its retrograde on october 8th. venus
column5: enters retrograde today (october 5th). when venus stations direct on november 16th
column8: goes into retrograde on the same day.

column1: all of this information hit me like a ton of bricks. i had already been thinking a lot about venus’s retrograde
column2: and how we enter it with venus in scorpio
column3: the sign of desire and passionate emotions. this
column4: in combination with the current conversation around sexual assault in society as of late
column5: called to mind the importance of our desires
column6: and how to prioritize what we want and need with others and with ourselves.

column1: the smallest amount of shaming or neglecting can completely skew our sense of desire
column2: and transform what should be a powerful and intuitive gift of direction
column3: into something we want to push down
column5: or somehow triumph over. this is especially true for queer people
column7: and likely all groups of systematically oppressed individuals. the fact is our needs are not prioritized
column8: and our desires are seen as secondary (and often times for queer people
column9: perverse). this all really came to a beautiful resolution for me upon listening to the most recent episode of the queer witch podcast
column10: where @thequeerwitch talks about desire as a tool for manifestation
column11: as well as overcoming shame and trauma around our sacred sense of desire. (cw: this episode discusses sexual assault!) this episode blew my mind. it called out to various aspects of my life
column12: all of the ways my desire has been stolen
column14: or mutilated by society and my own shame. my desire to embody my gender truthfully had been shamed by cisnormativity and transphobia. my desire to love who i love has been shamed by homophobia and transphobia.

column1: 314154;instagram;2018-10-05 15:24:39;FALSE;"رنویر سینگ و دیپیکا پادوکن در نشست خبری امروز راجب بحث بین تانوشری و نانا صحبت کردند.
رنویر گفت:ازار و اذیت هر کسی اشتباس. اگر هم این اتفاق افتاد شجاعت زیادی میخواد که در مکان های عمومی راجبش صحبت بشه. شما باید به این فرد توجه کنید. اگر این اتفاق افتاده کاملا اشتباس.

دیپیکا هم گفت: من احساس میکنم جنبش #metoo در رابطه با جنسیت نیست. این درباره پیروزی بعد از اشتباه هست. من فکر میکنم هرکسی با هر نوع تبعیض یا هر گونه مورد سو استفاده قرار میگیره ، ما به عنوان مردم باید ازشون حمایت کنیم. این درباره زن و مرد یا زن در مقابل مرد نیست. بیایید به هیچ وجه این مسائل رو اشتباه نکنیم. این هیچوقت درمورد جنسیت نیست.
همچنین بالاخره رنویر و دیپیکا به سوال هایی که راجب ازدواجشون میشد جواب دادند‌.

رنویر در جواب سوال ""عروسی شما چه زمانی برگزار میشه"" گفت:کی؟ کجا؟ شما هر روز دارید اینو تو مجلات میخونید. رنگ لباس من، برنامه عروسی ، مهمونا قراره به ما چی کادو بدن ، ظاهرا همه چیز مشخص شده. پس شما همه چیز رو راجبش میدونید اما یه چیزی هست که شما اولین نفری هستید که میدونید.
سوال بعد از دیپیکا پرسیده شد که ایا شما در ۲۰ نوامبر ازدواج میکنید؟ و دیپیکا گفت: عروسی های زیادی تو نوامبر قراره برگزار بشه.

column1: رنویر گفت:ازار و اذیت هر کسی اشتباس. اگر هم این اتفاق افتاد شجاعت زیادی میخواد که در مکان های عمومی راجبش صحبت بشه. شما باید به این فرد توجه کنید. اگر این اتفاق افتاده کاملا اشتباس.

دیپیکا هم گفت: من احساس میکنم جنبش #metoo در رابطه با جنسیت نیست. این درباره پیروزی بعد از اشتباه هست. من فکر میکنم هرکسی با هر نوع تبعیض یا هر گونه مورد سو استفاده قرار میگیره ، ما به عنوان مردم باید ازشون حمایت کنیم. این درباره زن و مرد یا زن در مقابل مرد نیست. بیایید به هیچ وجه این مسائل رو اشتباه نکنیم. این هیچوقت درمورد جنسیت نیست.
همچنین بالاخره رنویر و دیپیکا به سوال هایی که راجب ازدواجشون میشد جواب دادند‌.

column1: 314159;instagram;2018-10-05 15:25:45;FALSE;"this kavanaugh shit is absolutely fucking ridiculous. the guy clearly isn’t fit to be a judge
column2: let alone on the supreme godamn court. he lied under oath
column3: he acted like a spoiled child
column4: he cried in front of other senators
column5: he tried to pass off a 30 year old calendar as evidence
column6: and now his friends from yale all revoke their backing for him. when will this shit end? when the fuck will people take this for what it is? a privileged white piece of shit asshole of a human being sexually assaulted a fifteen year old girl and america wants to push him through to a life time appointment? what the actual fuck? even if he didn’t do it
column8: the way he’s behaved should disqualify him immediately. if a woman ever behaved the same way he did in front of the senate judiciary
column9: she would have been labeled “hysterical” or “unhinged” (just like serena williams was labeled last month) and this is the definition of sexism you dumb fucking (mostly) privileged white men who say sexism is in the past. how was this any different than the anita hill hearing? it’s been 30+ years and nothing has fucking changed. it makes me sick to my fucking stomach to watch yet another privileged white man sit up and spew his entitled bullshit.

column2: i’m not american but i am a woman. a woman herself who can say #metoo because every damn woman can say that. i don’t know any women who can say not #metoo because that’s just how damn common it is to be a victim of sexual assault or sexual harassment. it’s time to stop this bullshit and to stand up and say no. no
column3: we don’t want a sexual predator on the supreme court. no
column4: we don’t believe his lies! no
column7: i don’t owe you a damn thing.

column1: putting someone like kavanaugh on the highest court in america sends the message “we don’t give a fuck” to all women
column2: all over the world. is that really where we are right now?

column1: to all the women who have been a victim to sexual violence
column2: or any violence; i believe you. we believe you. let’s stand together and shout at the top of our lungs; no!

column4: make your opinion known. believe survivors
column5: it’s the least we can do. #timesup #believesurvivors";;en;#metoo

column1: i went to a rave where i didn’t sneak in - 16 and up were allowed - there was no alcohol but there were party drugs. i remember very little from the evening
column2: except that i was a virgin when i arrived. the “i don’t knows” are the holes in my story that have haunted me for decades. all i do remember is that
column3: in the middle of the night
column4: i woke up in a hotel room across town
column7: or the man with me. all i knew in that moment is that i was no longer a virgin. i was so scared and ashamed that i asked for his name and number before he left. i “dated” that person in a vain attempt to make sense of the situation - like i’d actually chosen him
column8: or that somehow there were feelings
column9: but i knew it was somehow my fault and i had to make it right. my life went into a tailspin where i tried to numb and even left home to live with him. i used to be thankful that he didn’t hit me as i found out he had all of his previous girlfriends. i was 16.

column1: i know why women don’t come forward. i’ve told this story to exactly 3 people that aren’t my therapist. i’ve typed and deleted and typed and deleted and typed and deleted this message over and over. i first told this story when i was 36 years old
column2: and even continued to blame myself in the retelling - and still blame myself another 5 years later if i’m being truthful. it wasn’t until my therapist forced me to say the word rape that i ever even attempted to come to terms with what happened to me that night. i told her it was my “first time” and she refused to let me talk about it in innocent ways as if it had been normal. i spent the next 22 years trying to make sense of why i was such a failure

column2: and even continued to blame myself in the retelling - and still blame myself another 5 years later if i’m being truthful. it wasn’t until my therapist forced me to say the word rape that i ever even attempted to come to terms with what happened to me that night. i told her it was my “first time” and she refused to let me talk about it in innocent ways as if it had been normal. i spent the next 22 years trying to make sense of why i was such a failure

314239;instagram;2018-10-05 14:58:00;FALSE;here’s our exciting news! 👕 i was told to turn a bad experience that we’ve recently gone through into something positive. i thought hard about that and here is it! 🤗 i’ve created a #becauseinclusionmatters t-shirt line on represent.com. there is only one youth option right now (the first shirt shown, swipe left ➡️) but i will introduce more if i have the interest! i am giving all profits to easter seals west kentucky to put toward their fundraising through the telethon. as a part of a conversation i had with a certain someone’s assistant, i said, “no one deserves to be disrespected and with the #metoo movement and the lgbtq inclusion awareness, we need to also add people with disabilities to that conversation”. so, here’s my little effort to help start/continue that conversation, i hope you enjoy! horrendous but not uncommon stories and naming names. just like what brave university students did several months ago. they are building a narrative that says: no more will we stay quiet, we will share, shame and bld solidarities. more power to these women. but this does not mean that those of us who choose not to speak up or not to speak up now are less brave. we too live with our wounds. we column1: this past month has been hard as a survivor. i know it's been hard for many of you. i've stayed silent about some of my assaults. i'll probably never go into detail what happened as a child or in college. those men will never be prosecuted. at least not because of me. there is guilt for that. but for the many reasons that i'm sure several of you understand
column2: i couldn't go through with charges. but my assault 2 years ago finally gave me a voice & i knew i couldn't be silent. i knew the man needed to be behind bars. i felt like it was our responsibility to do so. i was victim blamed. i was told i was in the wrong. i'll never understand how people do that. how people don't just say
column3: ""i'm so sorry."" how people will act like they know my situation. or tell me what i should've & shouldn't have done. i don't remember what i was wearing for any of my past assaults. the man that hit me
column4: i couldn't even remember his face. if it hadn't been for my friend there we wouldn't have had a case. but yet it happened. it happened at no fault of ours & we were still victim blamed. 2 years later
column5: he's in prison. with a total of 5 accounts he was given 60 years. i don't take lightly how that day changed his life or sentencing the judge gave him. but that day also changed my life as a mom
column7: & a person. my other assaults were different. i had convinced myself that i had done something wrong in those cases. that i was to blame. as faulty as that thinking was
column8: it helped me distance myself. i think that's how we all try & cope. if we can just find blame
column10: & give reason to what happened to us or others then we'll feel better. this time though i was stronger. i had my voice and i used it. it's still hard. for the most part i've learned how to ground myself. i use a coping technique that my therapist taught me. at times even in daylight
column12: paved trails my heart & breath still seem to freeze for a moment while running. that's when i use my senses to ground me
column13: to bring me back to reality. i listen. i don't wear earbuds so this is easy. i listen for footsteps

the second was the importance of not being a bystander. the monster in this story is without the isis militants. but nadia details the dire consequences for others when we stand by

column2: i found this book timely. you may think your one voice doesn’t have an impact
column3: but it does. it impacts your friends
column5: and adds to a collective voice that can instigate lasting change. it’s up to those that make themselves heard what kind of change that is. i never want to see a repressive society like the one in vox become a reality. i know i would not survive a one hundred words a day limit. and yeah

column7: but there are so many other ways to lose your voice. so
column8: i urge you all to speak out now
column9: and let your elected representatives know what matters to you. call your senator. attend a march. step out of your bubble to talk with people that have different opinions. don’t let them bully you into silence. and

column12: you’ve already given them your voice. @cvdalcher

column1: so he was guilty of groping and sexually assaulting me
and the repercussions for that type of conduct at a private law school in 2014? having him watch a movie about sexual harassment
column3: and then go on to get his degree

column1: when you allow a predator to rise to a position of power they can use that power to influence and perpetuate cycles of abuse and oppression. that is a terrifying
column2: institutional problem that goes far beyond one supreme court nomination

column1: i was pretty despondent after that
column2: but fortunately found an attorney at a victim’s rights organization who helped me file a formal complaint against the university to the office of civil rights within the department of education.

column1: ocr eventually opened an investigation into the university’s title ix practices
column2: and 3 and a half years later it’s still technically ongoing
column3: but not much has happened since early last year (hindsight: i should have just sued the school
column4: but at the time i was too traumatized to go through a process that could potentially involve public scrutiny
column5: and still had some faith in the federal government).

column2: the aftermath of reporting my sexual assault contributed more to my ptsd than the assault itself
column3: which many therapists have told me is not uncommon
column4: and why the past couple of weeks have been especially triggering for me and so many other survivors.

column1: i’m not trying to conflate my experience with what’s happening on the national stage
column2: nor do i want to dissuade anyone from reporting what happened to them
column3: but rather i hope to shine a light on why some people choose not to come forward with their sexual assault
column4: and take some of the shame out of discussing it openly if that is what someone chooses to do.

column1: the topic of sexual assault & harassment is extremely triggering

column1: 314344;instagram;2018-10-05 14:01:44;FALSE;"we practice the warriors so that we may become warriors. •
to either be the victim of your circumstances.
or you can be a warrior of your circumstances.
where do you feel bound and helpless?
feel the fire of rage that burns chaotically when freedom has been revoked. allow its power to bring you to the ashes so the phoenix of your soul may rise!
when you fight back in the areas where you feel powerless
column2: you liberate everyone else being held down as well!

this is not a democrat vs republican issue. this is about understanding that men and women are so often silenced from speaking up about assault and/or abuse.

column1: i don’t love alexander. i don’t think i ever did. i was sure at the time that i had never loved anyone as much as i loved him. but as is the ever changing
column2: ever evolving human condition i have reimagined my understanding of love
column3: as i’ve experienced and grown through it. no
column4: i do not and didn’t ever truly love alexander but he is the last man i was addicted to and he’ll remain the last. alexander came into my life at exactly the wrong time. i’m convinced that had he come to me at any other point i would have rejected him immediately
column5: generally i’m attracted to people who inspire me and alexander is the very opposite of what i regard as inspiring. he’s a jobbing comedian who refuses to have a stable income and is often financially dependant on others
column6: he’s deeply depressed and has little to no idea how his lack of self care effects the people who care about him
column7: he’s your typical guy who thinks the world should change to better suit his already mounting position of privilege
column8: as i said - not someone i’d normally regard as inspiring but when he found me i was more broken and further from being myself than i had ever been. just a few days after our initial lustful tryst i ended up in the crash room of homerton hospital having attempted suicide (and almost succeeded). i’d been seeing a man before him - chris. chris remains the most frightening and unbalanced person i have ever met and i say that without hyperbole. he was sexually violent
column10: frantic and compulsive. i’d been trying to rid chris from my life for almost a full twelve months when i met alexander. now alexander isn’t (wasn’t at that point) a bad guy. a lame guy
column11: but not a bad guy. and i loved the way he loved me. he made me feel worthy of praise and attention. something i hadn’t felt for years before meeting him. like a beaten dog i can’t deny i lashed out at him all while wanting his love an attention. fearful that his attention would turn to humiliation and eventually sexually it did. which i won’t deny initially i was into... but there came a point. there came a point where i was not ok and didn’t know what to do. the threat of violence

i've been working on a project to #decolonize #socialenterprise and help folks work together to #regenerate our global #ecosystem and practice #belovedcommunity. you can read more about that in other posts to this blog or do a search for #decolonialbiznessworld on this platform or elsewhere if you're #curious.

column1: the focus of this post is the lessons i've learned from #linkedin.
i didn't plan to create a method of #businesseducation aimed at #reparations and #decolonization. it just happened. decolonial bizness world came to me post-#hack.

column2: for the last four years i've been the #target of hackers
column3: some known and others not. you can find posts on being hacked in the archive of writings you see on linkedin if you search my writing. i won't include links directly because
column5: that's not the focus. this #tidbit is for context.

column2: after many hacks of small and large impact
column3: i lost everything in what i've come to call a ""#fullstack hack."" in the world of #engineering
column4: a full stack #developer is someone who handles all aspects of digital systems
column5: from databases to servers and clients to #apps. i use the term full stack hack to speak to my life after i lost access to:

column1: 1️⃣ the digital #archives that stored my papers such as half a completed #book manuscript
column3: and notes from more than a decade;

column1: 2️⃣my personal and academic email accounts; and
no joke. my phone got smoky and was #toast in mere minutes. the smoke effect was a sight to behold. it started in the bottom right corner and kept going and growing until goodbye #smartphone.
all this happened within a week or so. i don't recall the details or exact timeline; i was terrified and the consequences were swift and long-lasting. posts from that time also appear in this archive
column2: as this platform was one of the few i was able to access during that full stack hack of my life/work.

i've used this blog and platform to share drafts and more polished work. i've made edits and even complete deletions to what you can view -- and #metoo. the digital imprint remains in the cloud. #timesup

everything is crushing - why why why are women not being believed? and moreso when are men in positions of power whether that be a university or a government going to start accepting the repercussions of their own actions? so often victims of assault and harassment are blamed for ruining the careers of the perpetrator, when will everyone accept that the perpetrator has ruined their own career with their own actions. we all have the right to be respected and to use our voice to speak the truth and call out those who don’t respect us. in my experience i was told by an educational instutition who own experiences, whether in public or to friends and colleagues, we push a little bit further forward each time and let people know that this behaviour will no longer be tolerated or hushed up. we have a voice. women like dr blasey ford and anita hill have been through the trauma of questioning and scrutiny from the media for all of us and wednesday’s child just want to say thank you and we column1: my journey to hell and back began eighteen years ago. whether he was a charmer or i had been naive

column2: the trap had been laid and i was in it. on the day of the reception
column3: the stage had been set for what was to come. ""lift your head for photography or i’ll nail your neck""
column4: was the forewarning comment with many other tell-tale signs
column5: yet denying myself the reality. i chose to think it did not happen
column6: marriage then being a fairy tale. i lived in a violent marriage for years. after a brief honeymoon phase
column7: began the black and blue days. life became a cauldron of fear

column1: i fell for his occasional apologies and infrequent promises. i began to think he suffered from some psychological issues and i would rescue him
column2: thinking love and compassion were my armour.

column1: when his violence began to be directed at my son
column2: i changed. i started reading on self-esteem and positive affirmations. my son has been god sent
column3: while i may have given birth
column4: he truly gave me life. children are the only and most worthy assets of a painfully regrettable past.

column1: there is god and there is you. leaving an abusive relationship is the only choice. it is not your fault and you are not alone. reach out to people and support groups. after having set myself free
column2: i know it is possible. everyone has a right to live in dignity
column3: free from fear of violence or harm. i have felt angry
column4: and jilted by the justice system
column5: but i haven't given up. hang in there ~you are not alone!"" nikhath

column1: 314509;instagram;2018-10-05 12:23:46;FALSE;"that time in high school when i thought i was so fat.
i look back at this picture of my 17 year old self and wish i was ""this"" fat right now!! lol

column2: i have to wonder what my body image would have been like if i didn't grow up in the 90s. a time when nobody talked about body image or body positivity. we didn't have social media to connect us outside of our bubbles. there was zero diversity in the media when it came to bodies.

column1: i also thought i was a fat whale with no confidence about my body because of how boys treated me. they told me i was fat.
if you weren't a size 4 with a thigh gap
column2: you were garbage. boys thought it was their right of passage to tell you this.

i was bullied because of my weight. it was never by other girls. it was always by boys. why were they so obsessed over my body? why were they so offended that i was fat? why did that bother them so much?

column1: that has made me think about the connection to our body image and the #metoo movement. i don't have the answers right now. i just want to open the conversation.
my body image and validation was coming from the way boys (and later men) treated me. i think a lot of us as women have done this without realizing or recognizing it. well
column2: it's time to take back our power and our bodies.

column1: 314517;instagram;2018-10-05 12:25:45;FALSE;"they tell blatant lies. they deny something ever happened even though you have proof.
they use what is near and dear to you as ammunition. they wear you down over time.
their actions do not match their words. they throw in positive reinforcement to confuse you. they know confusion weakens people.
they project. they try to align people against you. they tell others that you are crazy. they tell you that you are crazy.  they tell you everyone else is a liar.
this is psychological warfare. this is abuse.

column1: 314533;instagram;2018-10-05 11:22:49;FALSE;the day after.. why now?  i feel raw
column4: i feel some relief but mostly i feel like i lived to tell my story. i lived through reliving it. and more than ever
column5: i am sure i lived through what happened to me so i could help other childhood trauma and assault survivors. i’m not angry anymore
column6: i let the anger go a long time ago
column7: thankfully.  i’m not even really sad anymore either although i cried more last night than i have since my mom died. and i feel like that’s exactly what i needed to do. i told my story to 10 women that i didn’t know.  most of the people i love know my whole story
column8: a few others know part of my story but last night i let it all go in front of these women.  i purged it all. i opened my wounds
column10: and cleaned them all out.  and the women last night understood and cried with me.  today i feel some peace for letting it out. what i want right now is to keep healing
column11: whatever that looks like.  i want to forgive the people in my life that didn’t know what to say or do to help me when it happened. i want them to know
column12: i know they did the best they could to help me. my story is not an easy thing to hear and i can imagine if someone i loved... my child
column15: my nieces would’ve told me that happened to them
column16: i would’ve probably not known how to handle it either. so i want to let that go
column17: and today i feel like have a little bit. and i want to be ready to let the rest of it go
column18: too. but for those people who think something that happened 40 years ago is something i should be over by now
column19: please educate yourself. there is no expiration date on healing and trauma and assault is something that alters your life forever.  my #whynow is because i want this to stop blocking my successes and the happiness i have in my life. i want to stop punishing myself.  i want to stop hurting the people i love by not trusting them or pushing them away.  i want to know i’ve survived this as close to a whole human as i possibly can be.  i want to use my experience to help other survivors... we’ll never be “over it” but we can get through it!  #whynow #survivor #metoo;;en;#whynow

column1: 314538;instagram;2018-10-05 11:55:29;FALSE;”du kanske kan skaffa ett jobb på mac donalds?”. har jag hört ca femtioelva gånger denna vecka. senast av min gynekolog - igår - som kom på lösningen på alla mina problem medan hon satt mellan mina ben o hade instrumenten kvar i min fitta som blottade min livmoder. jag kanske borde skaffa ett jobb på mac donalds? det gifter sig så bra med ptsd alkoholism o heltidsstudier. det är inte direkt ett stressigt yrke. det är inget tidskrävande yrke. om man jobbar skift på mac donalds medan man pluggar går ju livspusslet ihop! särskilt om man har ptsd
column2: panikångest och dricker sig full innan kl 15 varje dag. det känns ju rimligt. knappt hundra spänn i timmen för att flippa burgare o fritera pommes. det är taket. det är dit jag vill nå! så underbart det vore att utöver heltidsstudier
column4: polisutredning och alkoholism (och rännskita) jobba skift på donken. alla våras dröm. låg lön och maximal stress. det är drömmen. min våta dröm. att jobba på en snabbmatsrestaurangkedja och tjäna vad jag ”tjänar” per timmes sexträff på tre skift. jag har ju ett så stressfritt liv. det skulle va skönt med lite mer press. lite mer krav
column6: lite mer ansvar. jag kan ju faktiskt jobba på donken. detta drömyrke - en sån oas - en karriär värd att dö för. not. just nu kan jag få några hundralappar för att suga kuk. det tar 5 minuter. och jag behöver inte göra ett skit mer än att dyka upp. full som fan. och med panikångest. men visst
column7: rimligt med 6 timmar på mac donalds istället. ungefär lika ansträngande. nästan lika bra betalt. not. nästan rimligt. not. donken är inte något ställe som skulle funka för mig. tror inte man får vila och ha panikattack eller va full på jobbet?! så sluta råda mig om att jobba där. det är helt orimligt. mentalt frisk medelklass kanske pallar detta. inte en traumatiserad alkoholist. #metoo #prostitution #utanskyddsnät #intedinhora #jagärless;;en;#metoo

column1: we tackled a lot of issues that day. i was proud to be on the team for mental health awareness
our industry has done a shit job providing mental health support to its workforce. we work long and unconventional hours to keep things running for blissfully unaware customers and diners. -
it can be really tough and isolating. it leads to all kinds of stress
not to mention the physical toll it takes and the strength you need to keep going for up to 65 hours per week or more💪🏻.
we work over holidays and weekends
column3: for generally low wages. compound that with rampant discrimination
column4: wage gaps and harassment; it’s really fckin’ hard.

column2: low wages and general stigma in regards to mental health issues make care out of reach and not an option for so many.

column1: we need to do better as an industry. and we need people with a platform to speak up and advocate for those who can’t. we need solutions. -
@monroesarahjane had an awesome idea that she brought to the table and we ran with it
i’m confident a solution is in the works and on the way. even if it doesn’t happen overnight.
here’s to fighting for better standards

column1: 314574;instagram;2018-10-05 11:31:41;FALSE;"today i did some searching - looking for resources on what it takes for men to be men. to be successful feminists. what does that even look like? can men be feminists? what is it to be a man in today's society and climate? do we have to apologise for the bad men who represent us? do we have to take a step back
column2: away from the #metoo movements because we have enjoyed privilege for centuries? how can we use our platform to celebrate and promote those around us? is it even our place to do such a thing?

column1: i have been struggling for answers to these questions for a while now and i think i am probably not alone. i also think it would be a shame if somehow we as men drop our responsibilities and are not involved in any conversations. men have some serious issues that could benefit hugely from engaging with movements such as feminism and it is our chance to get involved.
i think this is particularly important for white
how does a demographic that represents so much oppression and tyranny over so many years make a change to their identity?

we should not feel guilty and apologetic for the horrible men that let us down. we need to take responsibility and show the marginalised and oppressed demographics of society that we are ready to listen and open to change.

column2: by being open and receptive we are not to use it as some form of alpha move. i will not state i am a feminism to make myself feel better than another man. i will not look down at what i deem to be an ignorant man and pretend i am better. that is toxic masculinity at its most socially accepted. let's stop making everything a competition and open our ears.

i think this is particularly important for white
how does a demographic that represents so much oppression and tyranny over so many years make a change to their identity?

we should not feel guilty and apologetic for the horrible men that let us down. we need to take responsibility and show the marginalised and oppressed demographics of society that we are ready to listen and open to change.

column2: by being open and receptive we are not to use it as some form of alpha move. i will not state i am a feminism to make myself feel better than another man. i will not look down at what i deem to be an ignorant man and pretend i am better. that is toxic masculinity at its most socially accepted. let's stop making everything a competition and open our ears.

column1: on this page i will be sharing all resources i deem helpful in our quest to understand how best we can contribute to loving society and in turn love ourselves.";"today i did some searching - looking for resources on what it takes for men to be men. to be successful feminists. what does that even look like? can men be feminists? what is it to be a man in today's society and climate? do we have to apologise for the bad men who represent us? do we have to take a step back
column2: away from the  movements because we have enjoyed privilege for centuries? how can we use our platform to celebrate and promote those around us? is it even our place to do such a thing?

column1: 314587;instagram;2018-10-05 11:38:07;FALSE;"i’ve been really quiet this week. it’s not been an easy week to be a survivor of sexual assault
column2: and i have had so many feelings rolling around
column3: as i’m sure many of you have too. enough is enough. we have been silent too long
column5: the echoes of witch hunts ringing in our ears.

column1: this isn’t a pretty or sanitary analogy
column2: but i’ve likened the kavanaugh hearing and trump’s mocking of dr ford to the bursting open of an infected wound. no healing can occur before all the yucky hidden stuff inside comes bursting to the surface. generations of toxic
column4: patriarchal abuses of power are bubbling up. because we as a society need to witness and understand the full extent of this brutality and control.

column1: and every time we raise our voices
column2: speak the truth and gather in solidarity
column3: we weaken the imbalanced power dynamic of patriarchal rule. we don’t want revenge
column4: we just want respect and equality. and to be safe

column1: 314590;instagram;2018-10-05 11:38:36;FALSE;"never in a million years did i think i’d be getting up this early to workout. to work on me. to commit myself to me. it’s most certainly not selfish to decide to take care of yourself for once. you always hear people say that because you’re a wife or mother you stop caring for yourself
column2: and while that’s true i don’t think that was the case with me. i think i just didn’t care enough about myself to want to improve.

column1: something has switched and i’m so thankful it has. maybe it’s all this #metoo talk or how i see women all over the world empowering themselves
column2: but all i know is i’m worth it and so are you!

column1: a couple of weeks back i carried out a poll on my story
column2: asking all of you your thoughts on the #metoo movement. an alarmingly large number of you thought that it was overrated and insignificant. i’m here to share an experience with you that might just show you how common it is for men to misbehave with women in public in a way that make women feel unsafe and just plain afraid.

my friends and i wanted to go grab something to eat. the weather was pleasant so the four of us decided to walk to jalal sons which was 5 mins away from my friend’s house. here i’d like to add that my friend lives in a safe neighbourhood. we were just a street away from there when a white car slowed next to us. the car’s window rolled down revealing two boys sitting inside. the boy addressed us in fluent english so i can’t blame his absurdity on lack of education. “can i give you a ride?” the boy on the driving seat spoke. we were all speechless as we continued walking
column3: paying no attention whatsoever because that’s what we’re taught right? to ignore?

column1: the car continued at the same speed next to us for a few minutes before racing away. we sighed in relief. we called home and asked for a car to pick us up from jalal sons as we were now just one street away from it and waiting for the car would take more time.
little did we know that it wasn’t over yet. the boys circled around the street and by the time we got to the next street – they were back again. the same statement
column2: the same mockery and the same sense of uneasiness in us. all i could think about in that moment was why were they doing this? what sense of achievement were they feeling in making us feel the way that we were? did they think we were going to jump at the opportunity of a “ride” and go off into the sunset with them? we increased our pace and walked into jalal sons watching the boys park their car outside. we cursed under our breaths contemplating whether or not we should call the cops. we waited inside for the next 20 mins till they finally gave up and left.

column1: 314637;instagram;2018-10-05 11:14:55;FALSE;art is often underrated.  sharpness is sometimes overrated.  this is the only photo ive really edited in years where i feel the editing combines my thoughts and truly helps report the story with the nostalgia it brings to me.  this dad’s genuine smile just lights me up.  to me this picture reminds me that this year has taught me how often we scrutinize little things in life that really trivialize the big picture for ourselves and others.  it disconnects us from asking ourselves about our own criticisms and questions we have for others.  the way i edited this picture is so you can hold your phone out at arms length
column3: and just see how much more there is to see in life
column4: and how much clearer it really is when you consider the whole big picture
column5: rather than picking apart every little thing.  is your day worth being ruined by things youhave no control over? is your word worth more than someone else’s feelings and well being? are you really passionate about the things the world says you should be passionate about?  everyone deserves to learn their world at their own pace

column1: 314654;instagram;2018-10-05 10:34:35;FALSE;"studentafton presenterar en afton om ”metoo - ett år senare""
på årsdagen av #metoo bjuder studentafton och lunds studentkårer in till en afton om metoo
column2: rörelsen som under ett års tid till stor del präglat samhällsdebatten. i panelen kommer gudrun schyman
column3: ulrika rogland och ola sigvardsson att medverka. aftonen äger rum i universitetsaulan med start kl. 19(..). den 15:e oktober 2017 skrev alyssa milano den tweet som kom att bli startskottet för vad som kallats en av de största folkrörelserna i modern tid. genom metoo vittnade kändisar såväl som privatpersoner om övergrepp i hem och på arbetsplatsen vilket resulterade i en global kampanj mot sexuella trakasserier.

column1: ett år senare anordnar studentafton ett reflekterande panelsamtal där rörelsens betydelse för samtiden och framtiden diskuteras utifrån flera olika perspektiv. aftonen avslutas i vanlig ordning med en frågestund där du som åhörare ges möjlighet att bidra till samtalet genom att ställa frågor till gästerna.
gudrun schyman är en av sveriges mest namnkunniga politiker och en frontfigur för den moderna feminismen. som partiledare för feministiskt initiativ har schyman förespråkat sociala reformer
column2: skärpt lagstiftning och omfördelning av pengar och makt som en fortsättning på metoo-rörelsen.

column1: ulrika rogland är advokat specialiserad på vålds- och sexualbrott. i sin roll som jurist har hon vid flera tillfällen uppmärksammats för sitt arbete med bland annat kvinnor
column3: och hedersvåld. 2016 var hon sommarvärd i sommar i p1
column4: där hon bland annat berättar om sitt arbete mot sexuella övergrepp.

column1: ola sigvardsson arbetar sedan 2011 som allmänhetens pressombudsman. pressombudsmannen fick efter metoo in elva anmälningar mot tidningar för deras rapportering om händelserna kopplade till metoo. i tio fall av elva fälldes tidningarna i pressens opinionsnämnd.
moderator för aftonen är kristin nord
pris: 70 kr för medlemmar i studentlund
biljetterna köps via studentafton.se eller studentinfo i af-borgen.

column1: 314701;instagram;2018-10-05 09:58:10;FALSE;"the kavanaugh-ford hearings have been extremely upsetting.
christine blasey ford has made history…. .
this is an excerpt from my columbia university commencement speech i delivered in may to the class of 2018. .

column2: my work has given me first hand experience with the metoo movement. i’ve faced discrimination and harassment because of my gender
column4: and race. it’s been hard… and i often look back and beat myself up with the “would’ve

column1: i would have fought back harder.
i could have told someone sooner.

column2: i was lucky. i had wonderful mentors who believed and helped me.

column1: not everyone is as fortunate though. look around you. sitting in your row is someone who
column3: might be the victim of discrimination or harassment.

column2: and this is to both men and women
column3: is to speak up when it happens to you
column4: or to someone else. if you don’t
column5: you’ll be playing the “what if” scenario for years later.

column1: do not be silent. hashtag #metoo could just be a moment. it’s up to your generation to make sure it endures.

column2: speak up not just for the #metoo movement’s sake but
column3: for yourself also.  even if you may think you are under qualified
column6: or promotion; nothing in life lands in your lap. fight for what you want

column2: to the men— your job is not to succumb to the notion that setting quotas and ticking boxes solves your “diversity” problem. you also need to listen to women. you will need to mentor and be mentored by them
column4: value the women on your team.

column1: equality will not happen unless each and every one of you pushes for it.
you graduate as elites. you have the to change the workplace. to change policy
the question is—will you have the courage? speaking up might be risky. will you be daring enough to make those who discriminate and harass uncomfortable?
i hope so. i believe so. it’s the only way to transform workplaces into environments where gender and race take a back seat to hard work

column1: 314712;instagram;2018-10-05 10:06:10;FALSE;"thank you so much to all of our new followers! we hope you will join us in our work tackling #sexualviolence and #harassment across sussex. we were so delighted and privileged to receive a visit from the #dukeandduchessofsussex on wednesday
column2: and we're so grateful for the platform it has given us to talk about these issues to a wider audience.

column1: you can find out more about our work in our insta story or on our website. we work with recent and non-recent cases
column2: with survivors aged 0+. over the past year we have supported nearly 2
column4: and the numbers are increasing. whether it's the #metoo movement
column6: or just a shift in society that encourages survivors to come forward
column7: we've seen a marked increase in referrals but without an increase in funding to keep up.

column2: one of the best ways you can support us and our work is through donations if you're able (if not sharing our posts is always appreciated!). you can donate here:

column1: www.localgiving.org/appeal/supportsn or get in touch if you'd like to organise any fundraising activities/events!

column1: 314718;instagram;2018-10-05 08:56:51;FALSE;"this is such a heavy topic for me.. but i'm talking about it because i need to & i think this topic is worth talking about.

column2: i was probably 5 or 6. maybe even 7. but this was around the time i was sexually assaulted. it started when i was 5. at the time
column3: i didn't realize what was happening to me was bad. not many people know this even happened to me.. i found out when i was in the 4th grade that it was not okay. & i tried to tell an adult when i was 11
column4: but instead got asked if i was sure that happened and if i just said it because i didn't like the person. it sucked to not be believed like that. it made me never wanna tell anyone again. but nonetheless
column5: i persisted. i told my close friends
column6: they all supported me and helped me as much as they could. the last time i was assaulted by this person
column7: i was 16. i suffer from ptsd & nightmares because of it. it went on for 10 or 11 years. i felt like killing myself because my body was not mine & i felt like i was on autopilot all of the time. i wasn't me. i didnt even know who ""me"" was. i was so depressed and cried all of the time. it took me such a long time to understand & believe that it was not my fault. that i was a victim & that i did nothing wrong. i never spoke up about it after the first time i tried to back when i was 11 because the adult i turned to
column9: so who would? why would anybody? ive been following all of these posts and articles about the #metoomovement
column11: &it made me feel like i should share my story
column12: too. the last sentence in oprah's speech made me believe that real changes are happening & i want to be part of that. i stand with the victims
column14: and i support this movement. i want to work towards a world where nobody else has to say me

column1: 314796;instagram;2018-10-05 07:37:05;FALSE;"""harvey weinstein - chronik eines skandals"" in der ard mediathek ansehen: https://www.ardmediathek.de/goto/tv/56672086

jahrzehntelang galt harvey weinstein als der hollywood-produzent schlechthin. die filme seiner firma miramax (später the weinstein company) galten lange als oscar-garanten. die gesamte hollywood-prominenz riss sich förmlich um ein treffen mit ""onkel harvey""
column2: wie schauspielerin @gwynethpaltrow ihn einmal nannte. doch diese treffen endeten oft mit sexuellem missbrauch. in dem investigativen dokumentarfilm ""harvey weinstein: chronik eines skandals"" zeichnet us-regisseur jordan hill die geschichte vom aufstieg und fall des hollywoodmoguls harvey weinstein nach - dessen fehlverhalten die weltöffentlichkeit schockte. doch nicht nur das: eine bewegung entstand

column1: 314822;instagram;2018-10-02 07:21:45;FALSE;"i går kväll fick jag träffa ett fantastiskt gäng unga killar i 17- och 18- årsåldern.
killarna spelar i hammarby. den enda fotbollsklubben i världen
column3: som förespråkar heforshe och valt att ta jämställdhet på allvar. det är en del av hammarbys värdegrund och innan

column1: killarna skulle ha sin måndagsträning fick jag och eleonor @karamelli prata med dem om just detta.

jag berättade om mina egna erfarenheter inom lagidrott och om när jag själv var i deras ålder. jag berättade om hur jag under flera år ljög att jag blivit av med oskulden för att jag ville bli accepterad. jag berättade om en kompis vars föräldrar hade skilt sig och hur dåligt han mådde
column2: men vågade inte berättade det för någon utan höll det för sig själv.

column1: vi män måste tänka om och fatta att det är en otrolig styrka att visa känslor. vi måste stötta varandra.
en av killarna delade med sig om hur han lärt sig att hantera sina känslor på egen hand då han under en tid varit utan familj och vänner.

tyvärr tror jag inte att vi lyckades skapa någon form av förändring hos dessa killar. tyvärr tror jag inte att de kommer ändra sitt beteende bara för att vi stod och pratade en liten stund innan deras träning. men om vi lyckades få dem att tänka lite annorlunda eller åtminstone fick dem att förstå att man kan tänka annorlunda
column2: och att det är okej. så kanske vi är på rätt väg i alla fall.

column1: heres some vent i worked on
column2: i think i can count this as letting everything out of my system. i am happy now. im no longer emotionally abused. everything in this picture is what i feel represents what happened to me
column3: though its just the tip of the iceberg. i dont want to go into detail about what happened
column4: thats only for my close friends if they ever want to know. he was trying to turn me into him. he controlled me like no tomorrow. he cut off my connections with the only friends i had in real life. he accused me of ""fantasizing"" about real people because i had a favorite male character. he started the emotional roller coaster by cutting his arm for literally no reason. i didnt make him sad. i didnt do anything that could have caused him to cut his arm. i told him that i liked pain in a masochistic way
column5: and he was all normal about it (a false sense of security) and suddenly got pissed about it and cut his arm. i remember that exact moment
column6: i almost threw up because i was eating fucking cereal at the time.  he called me weak and pathetic. he called me a bitch. he called me dense
column9: and annoying. he told me fuck you like those were the only words he knew when he was upset. those words caused me physical pain in my throat and chest every single time. he told me he hated me. the person i was deeply in love with told me he hated me. he caused me to detransition because he told me ""while im with you
column10: someone who wants to be a boy
column11: im not spending time looking for the right girl."" i told him i would be a girl for him. it didnt last a week. 2 days later i landed myself in the mental hospital. all contact cut off. i was free. for a day. the day i got out he had the fucking balls to message me again. but i was in such a weak part of my life

column1: i let him in. two times we stopped talking and i was free
column2: and then he entered himself back into my life again. the last time
column3: he acted as if it was my fault. he used me. he decided that we could be friends with benefits. he played with my feelings. and suddenly
column4: he left. he found someone else. he broke me. and he left me broken
column5: with no friends like i used to have.

column1: 314834;instagram;2018-10-05 06:55:53;FALSE;"varför ska kvinnor behöva kämpa för sina rättigheter?
by maywor in kvinnor sex o njutning
idag är det 1 år sedan #metoo exploderade…
finns det någon kvinna som under hela sitt liv kan säga att hon aldrig blivit sexuellt trakasserad?
sedan är det alltid en tolkning vad är en sexuell trakassering?
men visst har vi alla fått en sexuell anspelning någon gång i livet..
blivit kallade för ord bara för att vi är kvinnor.
är det sedan en kvinna som tycker om att ha sex och törs visa det..
jaa hon står inte högt i kurs då .
när är det dags att göra en förändring?
det är ca 10 år sedan jag kände mig mogen att börja dejta igen efter min skilsmässa.
jag var ju bara 16 år när jag flyttade ihop med mannen jag skulle leva ihop med i 31 år.
inte hade jag haft en tokig tonårs tid
column2: nej min blev ansvarsfull redan när jag gick i nian.

column1: året är 2008 jag hade börjat landa i norrköping efter 1 år.
ensamheten gjorde att jag var mycket ute på nätet.
var ju inte alls svårt att få kontakt med män.
visst var det en rolig tid
column2: jag tog igen min tonårstid vid 48 års ålder istället.

column1: men den här tiden har även tagit mycket av min tillit till män.
det jag fick lära mig var att det finns inte mycket respekt till en kvinna som är ute och har lite kul.
jag ångrar aldrig den här tiden som varade i ca 2 år..
utan jag ser det hela som livserfarenhet..
den här tiden där jag lekte av mig har format mig mycket till den jag är idag.
framför allt har den format mig till att ha den kampen jag för idag.
alla kvinnors rätt att vara sexuella utan att dömas
jag vet ju hur min reaktion var när andra kvinnor berättade att en kvinna får absolut inte ha sex vid första dejten..
vad är det för skillnad mellan första och andra dejten frågan jag.
joo mellan de dejterna så höjdes min status som kvinna???
jag var ju en singel kvinna som tog igen lite roligt jag missade i mina unga år.
det har gått 10 år sedan den här tiden…
nej som sagt var jag ångrar ingenting..
mina sista 10 år har varit helt galna på ett annat sätt.
jag har hittat mig själv vem jag är och vad jag behöver för att må bra.

column1: the fact that every state has the same amount of us senators is a joke. north and south dakota have four senators while california has two
column2: and washington d.c. and puerto rico have zero. i mean what the actual fuck? do we really need two fucking dakotas?(no. no we do not.)🙄 the system was designed this way
column4: to work against the people and in favor of the conservative white male ruling elite. the senate as it stands today doesn’t come close to representing america’s diversity
column5: as it has a conspicuous pro-rural
column6: anti-urban bias that disadvantages democrats and progressives. we can change this corrupt system
column7: but we have to vote many more progressives into office in order to do that.

column1: the senate floor vote on kavanaugh will be happening this weekend. this means we need to call our senators like crazy over the next few days. more than anything
column2: we all need to call the three republican senators who have the best chance of voting against kavanaugh:
blow up their social media pages
column3: and fill their inboxes with emails begging them to do the right thing and reject kavanaugh. we can win this
column4: but in order to do that
column5: we all have to get involved.

column1: keep calling your senators to tell them that you stand with dr. christine blasey ford and demand that they vote no on kavanaugh.

column2: make sure you are registered to vote. you can register at vote.gov.

column1: the fact that every state has the same amount of us senators is a joke. noh and south dakota have four senators while california has two
column2: and washington d.c. and pueo rico have zero. i mean what the actual fuck? do we really need two fucking dakotas?(no. no we do not.)🙄 the system was designed this way
column4: to work against the people and in favor of the conservative white male ruling elite. the senate as it stands today doesn’t come close to representing america’s diversity
column5: as it has a conspicuous pro-rural
column6: anti-urban bias that disadvantages democrats and progressives. we can change this corrupt system
column7: but we have to vote many more progressives into office in order to do that.

blow up their social media pages
column3: and fill their inboxes with emails begging them to do the right thing and reject kavanaugh. we can win this
column4: but in order to do that
column5: we all have to get involved.

column1: 314907;instagram;2018-10-05 05:41:49;FALSE;first time at naropa this eve. 🙌 amazing that there is this flourishing buddhist university right here in the rockies! i found it interesting to hear lama & scholar ann klein speak tonight about what she calls the “open secret
column2: ” the ultimate nature of mind or awareness according to tibetan buddhist philosophy & practice at the intersection of tantra
column4: and madhyamika. i wanted to ask her how she would connect this wisdom with the reality that we are facing today in terms of the #metoo movement and the sexual assault scandals that have recently shaken the tibetan buddhist & ashtanga yoga communities
column5: not to mention my own personal experience with the hare krishna community in india. fortunately
column6: a similar question was raised by another attendee - none other than jules
column7: the tibetan translator who taught part of the yoga intensive that i attended this past summer with richard freeman & mary taylor at the yoga workshop also here in boulder! i felt blessed in our ashtanga intensive for many reasons
column8: one of them being that this conversation was part of our training - that my teachers recognized the importance of holding space to discuss the confusion around our “gurus” and the causes and conditions that may or may not have contributed to this kind of suffering and sense of betrayal. as spiritual seekers
column9: we all have to consider when/how/why do spiritual teachings
column10: (such as “nonduality” and “non-separateness” that point to the primordial intimacy between “self” and “other”) become perverted or debased into excuses
column12: and/or even licenses for abusive behavior

column1: 314910;instagram;2018-10-05 05:43:18;FALSE;"okay i have a few of things to say about brett kavanaugh.

1. why do they have to rush this. when they vote for a supreme justice they have to realize this is a huge deal. you can’t nominate a person who will be on the highest court of the most powerful country on the world
column2: when he might have raped teenagers in collage. if he might seem a little bit sketchy you have to take you’re time to make sure he hasn’t done anything wrong. also
column3: even without the sexual assault allegations this is the supreme court. that one single person on the supreme court will change millions of lives.

column1: 2. this is just more than a supreme court justice
column2: this will show young women all over america how we treat sexual assault allegations. if we nominate him as a supreme court justice without knowing he’s not a rapist. it shows that america doesn’t believe women
column4: mocked and made fun of for coming forward. to the point we’re we will still appoint them to the fucking supreme court without being sure if he’s a rapist or not.

column1: 3. why can’t just pick another person its not that hard
column2: there are a lot of more quality people out there that haven’t been accused of rape and doesn’t get fucking wasted every other day.

column1: thoughts for a sunday morning... ☀️🍃...i have become a ghost of who i used to be & who i know i’m supposed to be. over time i’ve let events & circumstances define me & weaken me....i’m climbing back though & yes i am flawed because i’m human but i feel it’s time for all humans to simply do better...be better humans for ourselves
column2: our fellow humans but especially we need to be better for our planet & all of the living beings that let us share it with them. 🌱

column1: my message is becoming more clear to me & i know there are so many people who are resisting hearing it. it’s not my intention to offend or be whollier-than-thou. but i’m fairly certain i will offend so i challenge you to stick around
column2: be uncomfortable & open your mind to the possibility that life on this planet isn’t just about us humans & that we can individually & collectively simply be better humans. 🙏🏼

column1: 314926;instagram;2018-10-05 05:53:25;FALSE;"we had an evening off yesterday and went to light night leeds an amazing free event in the city. this is the story of the dragon from the guide book.. (it’s on again tonight if you can make it..) in medieval times the town of leedis had six wooden gates designed to delay unwanted visitors
column2: collect tolls and protect the city. legend says that for many years the west ‘bar’ positioned near boar lane and city square was guarded by a dragon. however
column3: when the gates were no longer required the dragons use became obsolete. unable to kill the fearsome beast
column4: the citizens of leedis captured and chained it in a dungeon and left it to be forgotten. today
column5: hundreds of years later the dragon has awoken and is seeking vengeance.

column3: from the bottom of my heart
column4: thank you to @ladygaga for always being such a loud and powerful voice for us #survivors. trauma is something that truly can never be comprehended until it happens to you. gaga speaks from such a powerful place so deep in her core because she’s experienced it. i’ve experienced it. statistics say that 1 in 4 women will experience it in their lifetime. we need to #stoptheshame and #endthestigma around sexual assault. we need to be listening to our brothers and sisters that are coming forward. #imwithdrford #metoo

column1: 314949;instagram;2018-10-05 05:03:15;FALSE;"hard to believe we are one year in to filming nevertheless! read director @sarahmoshman reflect on that year: ✨✨✨✨✨✨✨✨✨✨✨✨✨✨✨✨✨
one year ago today i started making a documentary now titled nevertheless. i was 8 months pregnant
column2: i knew i had a daughter coming in to this world
column3: and i also knew i had many moments in my career where i felt like i didn’t have a voice
column4: and i wasn’t being respected. i was tired of hearing so many stories from my friends and co-workers about sexual harassment in and out of the workplace. so i did the only thing i really know how to do - pick up the camera and get to work. the next day
column5: the weinstein story broke. and the following week an avalanche of #metoo dominated our feeds finally ripping the bandaid off of this dialogue in our country.

column1: for the past year i have had the honor of talking with some of the brightest and most insightful minds about this topic as well as brave individuals who have shared their intimate and at times heartbreaking stories of harassment and assault. i feel more confident than ever that this film will do a lot of good in the world once it’s complete. i have certainly learned to question my own biases
column3: examine the ways in which i am complicit to these systems that don’t serve anyone
column4: and try to work towards what real

column1: i’m still very much on this journey and some days i feel like i’m drowning with a project of this magnitude
column2: but i want to take a moment to appreciate how far nevertheless documentary has come. change is possible. and the power of cinema is the best way i know how to help create it. 🎥 #nevertheless #timesup #believesurvivors";;en;#MeToo

получил трамп , а теперь кандидат в президиум верховного суда штатов кавано . престарелая самка , которая давала показания перед коллегией , спустя 36 лет явно не по собственной воле заявила о для аналогии , шкурыгина в свои 55 пришла бы на пусть говорят , и припомнила , как когда-то на вписке ей кто-то запустил по пьяне межножную ракету👀 а теперь инсайд . рассказываю только один раз про политический механизм , работающий на загнивающем западе ... итак , трамп мешает конгрессу и демократам , т.к человек неуправляем . если бы не налаженная система он стал бы вторым путиным . но и опозорить его друзей и ему близких . связи с россией и харассмент - новые инструменты + главные сми подконтрольны демократам + все меньшинства , обиженные , эмигранты , черные - вот главный
